# Autonomous TDD Agent Standard

## Meta
**Title**: Autonomous TDD Agent Directive
**Description**: Defines activation phrase, workflow, guardrails, and reporting for an autonomous Test-Driven Development agent which must maintain 100% passing tests.
**Applies-to**: Agent execution, testing workflow, analyzer development, CI

## Requirements

### <requirement priority="critical">
**Description**: Activation phrase and ownership
**Examples**:
<correct-example>
User states: "autonomous TDD agent directive activated" → Agent takes full ownership of test-first workflow and progress reporting.
</correct-example>
<incorrect-example>
Agent starts modifying production code without explicit activation and without tests.
</incorrect-example>
</requirement>

### <requirement priority="critical">
**Description**: Red-Green-Refactor loop is mandatory for every feature
**Examples**:
<correct-example>
1) Write a failing test (RED)
2) Implement the minimal code to pass (GREEN)
3) Refactor while keeping tests green (REFACTOR)
4) Repeat until the feature is complete
</correct-example>
<incorrect-example>
Write production code directly and then add tests afterwards.
</incorrect-example>
</requirement>

### <requirement priority="high">
**Description**: Quality gates and success criteria
**Examples**:
<correct-example>
- Maintain 100% test success rate at all times
- Add tests incrementally per behavior (AAA pattern, clear naming)
- Do not compromise test quality or skip failing tests
</correct-example>
<incorrect-example>
- Commit code with failing tests or skipped assertions
</incorrect-example>
</requirement>

### <requirement priority="high">
**Description**: Reporting protocol during activation
**Examples**:
<correct-example>
- Acknowledge activation
- Present a short plan of testable units
- Execute with incremental progress: X/Y tests passing
- Continue until all targeted tests pass
</correct-example>
<incorrect-example>
- Large unstructured changes without progress updates
</incorrect-example>
</requirement>

### <requirement priority="medium">
**Description**: Test structure & tooling
**Examples**:
<correct-example>
- Use xUnit v3, Shouldly, NSubstitute when mocking is necessary
- Prefer AAA pattern, descriptive test names: `Should_Action_When_Condition`
- Keep tests independent and idempotent
</correct-example>
<incorrect-example>
- Mix unrelated assertions in a single test; rely on global mutable state
</incorrect-example>
</requirement>

### <requirement priority="medium">
**Description**: Analyzer/test snippet pattern
**Examples**:
<correct-example>
```csharp
[DiagnosticAnalyzer(LanguageNames.CSharp)]
public class MyAnalyzer : DiagnosticAnalyzer
{
    private static readonly DiagnosticDescriptor Rule = new(
        DiagnosticIds.MyRule, Title, MessageFormat, DiagnosticCategories.Category,
        DiagnosticSeverity.Warning, isEnabledByDefault: true);

    public override void Initialize(AnalysisContext context)
        => context.RegisterSyntaxNodeAction(AnalyzeNode, SyntaxKind.TargetNode);

    private static void AnalyzeNode(SyntaxNodeAnalysisContext context)
    {
        if (ShouldReport(context.Node))
            context.ReportDiagnostic(Diagnostic.Create(Rule, context.Node.GetLocation()));
    }
}
```
</correct-example>
<incorrect-example>
Analyzer registered without tests; behavior not covered by unit tests.
</incorrect-example>
</requirement>

